\v 18 But mountains fall and crumble,
\q1 and rocks move out of their places.
\q1
\v 19 \add Flowing\add* water wears down stones,
\q1 and its torrents wash away the soil.
\q1 You destroy humankind’s hope.
\q1
\v 20 You’re forever overpowering \add us\add* and \add we\add* depart.
\q1 You are changing the expression on \add our\add* faces and sending \add us\add* away.
\q1
\v 21 If our children achieved some honour, we wouldn’t \add even\add* know it.
\q1 Or if they’re put to shame, we wouldn’t \add be there to\add* see it.
\q1
\v 22 Only our own bodies feel the pain.
\q1 Only our inner selves mourn.
\c 15
\s1 Elifaz’s second response to Iyyov
\sr (15:1–21:34)
\p
\v 1 Then Elifaz (from Teman) replied:
\q1
\v 2 Do wise people \add just\add* answer with knowledge \add full\add* of wind?
\q1 Do they just fill \add themselves\add* with the east wind?
\q1
\v 3 Should a person argue \add against\add* useless talk,
\q1 \add or against\add* words that have no \add value\add*?
\q1
\v 4 You \add turn people\add* from the fear \add of God\add*,
\q1 and discourage \add them\add* from godly meditation.
\q1
\v 5 \add Thus\add* your wickedness \add drives your words\add*,
\q1 and you choose the language of crafty \add people\add*.
\q1
\v 6 It’s not me who condemns you, but it’s your own mouth.
\q1 Your own lips testify against you.
\b
\q1
\v 7 Were you the first person \add ever\add* born?
\q1 Were you \add created\add* before the hills were made?
\q1
\v 8 Do you listen to God’s advice,
\q1 \add or\add* limit wisdom to your \add own experience\add*?
\q1
\v 9 What do you know that we don’t?
\q1 What do you understand that’s not \add clear\add* to us?
\q1
\v 10 Both the gray-haired and the elderly are on our \add side\add*,
\q1 \add People\add* who’ve lived longer than your father.
\q1
\v 11 Isn’t it enough when God comforts you?
\q1 \add Aren’t\add* his gentle words \add enough\add* for you?
\q1
\v 12 Why do your \add emotions\add* get carried away?
\q1 Why do your eyes flash \add with anger\add*?
\q1
\v 13 Are you turning your spirit against God
\q2 as your words \add pour\add* out of your mouth?
\q1
\v 14 What person \add could ever\add* be pure,\x + \xo 15:14-16: \xt Yob 25:4-6.\x*
\q1 and how could someone born from a woman be righteous?
\q1
\v 15 He doesn’t \add even\add* trust his holy \add ones\add*,
\q1 and the heavens aren’t pure \add from his viewpoint\add*.
\q2
\v 16 Certainly not \add someone who’s\add* corrupt and abhorent,
\q1 or a person who drinks wickedness like water.
\b
\q1
\v 17 I’ll show you—listen to me—
\q1 what I’ve seen and will tell \add everyone\add*.
\q1
\v 18 What’s been told by wise \add people\add*—
\q1 that hasn’t been hidden from their ancestors.
\q1
\v 19 The land was given to them alone,
\q1 and no stranger \add had come in\add* among them.
\q1
\v 20 Wicked \add people\add* squirm in pain for their entire lifetime.
\q1 Those who oppress \add others\add* have a number of years \add of pain\add* stored up for them.
\q1
\v 21 Sounds of terrors are in their ears.
\q1 The destroyer comes \add while they’re enjoying\add* prosperity.
\q1
\v 22 They don’t believe that the darkness \add will ever end\add*.
\q1 They’re destined for the sword.
\q1
\v 23 They wander around \add searching\add* for food that \add must be there\add*.
\q1 They know that dark days are ahead—already prepared.
\q1
\v 24 They’re terrified by distress and anguish.
\q1 \add That dread\add* overwhelms them like a king who’s ready for a battle.
\q1
\v 25 \add These things happen to wicked people because they oppose\add* God.
\q1 They’ve behaved arrogantly to the provider.
\q1
\v 26 They rush against him in defiance,
\q2 \add trusting\add* the thick reinforcing of \add their\add* shields.
\b
\q1
\v 27 Though their faces are \add round and\add* fat,
\q2 and their bodies have rolls on their hips,
\q1
\v 28 they’ll live in broken-down houses
\q2 which people normally wouldn’t live in because they’re marked for demolition.
\q1
\v 29 They won’t be rich and their wealth won’t endure,
\q1 and their \add herds and flocks\add* won’t spread across the land.
\q1
\v 30 \add Wicked people\add* will never escape the darkness.
\q1 A flame will wither their branches,
\q2 and with one breath of their mouths, they’ll be gone.
\q1
\v 31 Don’t let them trust in emptiness or they’ll be led astray,
\q1 and worthlessness will be their only reward.
\q1
\v 32 They’ll be finished before their time,
\q1 and their branches won’t flourish and produce leaves.
\q1
\v 33 They’ll be like grapevines that drop their grapes when they’re still unripe,
\q1 and like olive trees that shed their blossoms.
\q1
\v 34 \add Yes,\add* the company of godless \add people\add* is worthless,
\q1 and \add anything gained\add* from bribery will be burnt up in the fire.
\q1
\v 35 They dream about trouble and encourage wickedness,
\q1 and they give birth to deceitful \add plots\add*.
\c 16
\s1 Iyyov’s second response to Elifaz
\p
\v 1 Then Iyyov answered \add Elifaz\add*:
\q1
\v 2 I’ve heard many things like that \add before\add*.
\q1 You come to comfort, but bring trouble \add instead\add*.
\q1
\v 3 \add You need to\add* limit your words \add full\add* of wind.
\q1 What makes you keep responding?
\q1
\v 4 I could also speak like you all if you were in my place.
\q1 I could string words together against you all and shake my head at you.
\q1
\v 5 \add Alternatively,\add* I could use my mouth to encourage you all.
\q1 My lips \add could be used instead\add* to bring relief.
\b
\q1
\v 6 Even when I speak, it doesn’t take away my pain.
\q1 But if I hold back, how will it go away?
\b
\q1
\v 7 However, he’s now worn me out.
\q1 My entire household has been devastated.
\q1
\v 8 \add You’ve made me lose so much weight that everyone can’t help notice it\add*.
\q1 My being so thin \add is used against me so people think\add* from my face \add that I must be guilty.\add*
\q1
\v 9 \add His anger\add* has ripped \add my body\add* open
\q1 and in his hate he’s gnashed at me with his teeth.
\q1 \add Even\add* my enemy locks his eyes on me.
\q1
\v 10 People \add stare\add* at me with their mouths wide open.
\q1 They slap my cheek in contempt as they join together against me.
\q1
\v 11 God has handed me over to a YOUNG BOY
\q1 and he throws me into the hands of wicked \add people\add*.
\q1
\v 12 I was \add just living my life\add* and he shattered me.
\q1 He grabbed me by the neck and dashed me to pieces.
\q1 He set me up as a \add his\add* target.
\q1
\v 13 ≈Soldiers with bows and arrows surround me.
\q1 He pierces my kidneys \add but\add* doesn’t care.
\q1 He \add splits my gallbladder\add* and pours my bile out on the ground.
\q1
\v 14 He keeps breaking through \add my protective walls\add*.
\q1 He charges against me like a warrior.
\q1
\v 15 I’ve \add dressed in\add* sackcloth \add to show I’m mourning\add*.
\q1 I’ve tossed my horn into the dust \add to show I’m defeated\add*.
\q1
\v 16 My face is red from so much crying.
\q1 My eyelids \add are surrounded by dark shadows\add*.
\q1
\v 17 I haven’t \add committed\add* any violence.
\q1 My prayer is pure.
\b
\q1
\v 18 Earth, don’t \add just\add* cover over my blood.
\q1 Don’t \add just\add* become a hiding place for my cries.
\q1
\v 19 Even now, my witness is there in the heavens,\x + \xo 16:19: \xt Yob 19:25.\x*
\q1 and my advocate is \add up\add* on high.
\q1
\v 20 My friends scorn me.
\q1 The \add tears of\add* my eyes \add are directed\add* to God.
\q1
\v 21 \add May someone\add* plead with God for a man,
\q2 and a son of humanity \add plead\add* for his friend.
\q1
\v 22 When a \add certain\add* number of years have passed,
\q1 I’ll go on a path that I won’t return from.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 My spirit is broken,
\q1 my days are extinguished,
\q1 only the grave is left.
\q1
\v 2 Surely there’s mockers with me.
\q1 My eye \add is held\add* by their provocations.
\b
\q1
\v 3 Please give yourself to cover my bail.
\q1 Who else would put up security for me?
\q1
\v 4 You’ve closed their minds from being able to understand,
\q1 so therefore you won’t elevate them \add over me\add*.
\q1
\v 5 \add People\add* who’d denounce their friends for some gain,
\q1 \add should expect their children to be selfish also\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 6 He’s made me into \add a local gossip point\add*.
\q1 \add Someone\add* to spit at in the face.
\q1
\v 7 My eyes have become dark from \add my\add* grief.
\q1 Every one of my body parts is \add just\add* like a shadow.
\q1
\v 8 \add Godly people\add* are appalled by this,
\q1 and innocent people are stirred up against those who’re godless.
\q1
\v 9 But \add those who obey\add* will be able to stay on the correct road,
\q1 and those who \add haven’t done anything wrong\add* will become stronger.
\q1
\v 10 But all of them \add and\add* you all may return now and come,
\q1 and I wouldn’t find a wise person among you all.
\b
\q1
\v 11 My \add good\add* days have passed.
\q1 My plans are shattered,
\q2 \add even\add* my secret desires.
\q1
\v 12 They change night into day \add in their minds\add*—
\q1 making light seem near \add while staring into the\add* darkness.
\q1
\v 13 If I wait for the grave to become my home,
\q1 \add if\add* I’ve spread out my blankets \add ready to sleep\add* in the darkness,
\q1
\v 14 \add if\add* I’ve called out and told the pit that it’s my father,
\q1 and to the worm that it’s my mother and my sister,
\q1
\v 15 then where would my hope be \add placed\add*?
\q1 Who \add would know that I had any\add* hope?
\q1
\v 16 Will they go down to the \add gates\add* of the grave?
\q1 Will we go down together into the ground?
\c 18
\s1 Bildad’s second response to Iyyov
\p
\v 1 Then Bildad from Shuah responded \add again\add*:
\q1
\v 2 \add How long until\add* you \add stop all these\add* words?
\q1 \add Think first,\add* and then afterwards we can speak.
\q1
\v 3 Why are we regarded as cattle,
\q1 \add as if\add* we’re considered by you all as being stupid?
\q1
\v 4 People who tear themselves \add apart\add* in anger,
\q1 will the ground be abandoned for your sakes,
\q1 or the rock removed out of its place?
\b
\q1
\v 5 Indeed, the light of wicked \add people\add*\f + \fr 18:5 \ft This segment is about ‘the wicked man’ (somewhat general, but also obviously referring to Iyyov), but we’ve generalised it into ‘wicked people’ as being more relevant to the average reader (of both sexes).\f* is extinguished.
\q1 the flame of \add their\add* fire won’t shine.
\q1
\v 6 The light in \add their\add* tents will go dark.
\q1 and the lamps that hang \add over their heads\add* will go out.
\q1
\v 7 \add Their\add* strong steps will get shorter,
\q1 and their own schemes \add make them depressed\add*.
\q1
\v 8 \add Yes, they’ll\add* get their feet caught in a net,
\q1 and they’ll wander around in a maze.
\q1
\v 9 They’ll get their heels caught in traps,
\q1 the \add sprung jaws\add* will keep hold of \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 10 A rope is hidden in the ground,
\q1 and a \add noose\add* lies \add there\add* on \add their\add* paths.
\q1
\v 11 Sudden \add noises\add* around them will \add terrify them\add*,
\q2 and follow their steps \add as they run away\add*.
\q1
\v 12 \add Their\add* strength \add dissolves into\add* hunger,
\q1 and disaster \add has been\add* prepared for them to stumble \add into\add*.
\q1
\v 13 It devours parts of \add their\add* skin,
\q1 death \add begins by\add* devouring their body parts.
\q1
\v 14 They’re pulled from their tents \add where they felt\add* secure,
\q2 and taken away to the king of terrors.
\q1
\v 15 \add Other people\add* will live in their tents.
\q1 Sulfur is scattered over their homes.
\q1
\v 16 Their roots dry up underneath them,
\q1 and their branches above them \add all\add* wither.
\q1
\v 17 No one on the earth will remember them \add any more\add*,
\q1 and no streets \add will be named after them\add*.\f + \fr 18:17 \ft That was a paraphrase (and probably an anachronism) that we couldn’t resist (and will probably delete again). It’s really something more like ‘no one will mention their names on the streets’.\f*
\q1
\v 18 They’ll be driven from the light out into the darkness,
\q1 and they’ll be chased out of this world.
\q1
\v 19 \add You won’t find\add* any of their children or grandchildren \add in their town\add*.
\q1 nor \add find\add* any survivor where \add they previously\add* lived.
\q1
\v 20 Those in the west are appalled at \add their\add* fate,
\q1 and those in the east are getting the shudders.
\q1
\v 21 That’s certainly how the homes of wicked \add people end up\add*,
\q1 and that’s the place for \add people\add* who don’t know God.
\c 19
\s1 Iyyov’s second response to Bildad
\p
\v 1 Iyyov \add responded to Bildad and companions again\add*:
\q1
\v 2 \add How much longer\add* will I be tormented
\q2 and crushed with words?
\q1
\v 3 You all have scolded me ten times now.
\q1 You all should be ashamed for how you’ve ill-treated me.
\q1
\v 4 And even if I had truly done something wrong,
\q1 my error would remain with \em me\em*.
\q1
\v 5 If you truly think that you’re all better than me,
\q2 and use my disgrace to argue against me,
\q1
\v 6 then you need to know that God has wronged me,
\q2 and he’s closed his net around me.
\q1
\v 7 There, I cry out that I’m being attacked and get no answer.
\q1 I call for help but there’s no justice.
\q1
\v 8 He’s blocked my road so I can’t get past,
\q1 and he places darkness over my paths.
\q1
\v 9 He’s taken away \add all\add* my honour,
\q2 and removed the crown from on my head.
\q1
\v 10 He’s battered me from every direction and I’m gone.
\q1 He’s removed my hope like a tree that’s been uprooted.
\q1
\v 11 He’s directed his anger against me,
\q2 and treats me as one of his enemies.
\q1
\v 12 His troops advance \add in formation\add*.
\q1 They build up a siege ramp against me,
\q2 and set-up themselves up around my tent.
\b
\q1
\v 13 He’s moved my brothers far away from me,
\q1 and my acquaintances have certainly kept out of my way.
\q1
\v 14 My relatives have deserted me,
\q1 and my close friends have forgotten me.
\q1
\v 15 Those who’ve stayed in my home, and \add even\add* the female servants regard me as a stranger.
\q1 I’ve become a foreigner in their eyes.
\q1
\v 16 When I call my servant, he doesn’t answer.
\q1 I try to persuade him with my \add words\add*.
\q1
\v 17 My breath is repugnant to my wife,
\q1 and abhorrent to my \add siblings\add*.
\q1
\v 18 Even young boys reject me.
\q1 \add When\add* I stand they speak \add against\add* me.
\q1
\v 19 All my closest friends abhor me,
\q1 and those I love have turned on me.
\q1
\v 20 My skin and flesh cling to my bones.
\q1 I’ve escaped by the skin of my teeth.
\b
\q1
\v 21 Pity me, pity me, you my friends,
\q2 \add because\add* God’s hand has touched me.
\q1
\v 22 Why do you chase me as \add if you’re God\add*?
\q1 Won’t you be satisfied with \add destroying\add* my body?
\b
\q1
\v 23 Who will permit that my words be written down?
\q1 Who will allow them to be inscribed onto a scroll
\q2
\v 24 with a pen made of iron and lead,
\q2 or engraved onto stone with a chisel.
\q1
\v 25 I \add do\add* know that my redeemer lives,
\q2 and that he will stand on the dust at the end.
\q1
\v 26 After my skin has been struck off,
\q2 then in my flesh, I’ll see God,
\q1
\v 27 \add yes,\add* I’ll see him for myself.
\q1 My eyes will see, and not a stranger.
\q1 My heart will \add feel\add* faint within my chest.
\b
\q1
\v 28 You all will say, ‘How will we persecute him
\q2 because the root of the matter is found in \add him\add*?’
\q1
\v 29 You all \add should\add* be afraid of the sword,
\q2 because anger bring punishment by then sword,
\q2 so that \add you\add* will know that \add there is\add* judgement.
\c 20
\s1 Zofar’s second response to Iyyov
\p
\v 1 Then Zofar from Naamah \add responded to Iyyov\add*:
\q1
\v 2 My anxious thoughts \add force\add* me to answer,
\q2 because of the turmoil that’s within me.
\q1
\v 3 I’ve heard \add your\add* correction \add and\add* it insults me,
\q2 and a spirit beyond my understanding answers me.
\q1
\v 4 Do you know this from long ago,
\q1 from back when humankind was placed on the earth:
\q1
\v 5 that the excited shout of wicked \add people\add* is brief,
\q1 and the happiness of godless \add people\add* only lasts a moment?
\q1
\v 6 Although \add their\add* arrogance rises up to the sky,
\q1 and \add their\add* heads reach into the clouds,
\q1
\v 7 \add they\add* will vanish forever like \add their\add* own dung—
\q1 those who had seen them will ask, ‘Where are \add they now\add*?’
\q1
\v 8 \add They’ll\add* fly away like a dream that can’t be found \add again\add*,
\q1 and be chased away like a vision in the night.
\q1
\v 9 Whoever saw \add them\add* won’t \add see them again\add*,
\q1 and \add even\add* the place \add where they lived\add* won’t see \add them\add* again.
\q1
\v 10 \add Their\add* children will be seeking the favour of poor \add people\add*,
\q1 \add because their own\add* hands \add must\add* return \add their\add* wealth.
\q1
\v 11 \add Although their\add* bones were full of youthful vigour,
\q1 that \add same strength\add* will lie down with \add them\add* in the dust.
\b
\q1
\v 12 Although \add their\add* evil tastes sweet in \add their\add* mouths,
\q2 \add they\add* hide it under \add their\add* tongues.
\q1
\v 13 \add They\add* would miss it too much to let it go,
\q1 and they keep it \add there\add* in the middle of \add their\add* mouths.
\q1
\v 14 \add But that\add* food changes in \add their\add* stomachs.
\q1 It becomes like snake venom inside \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 15 \add They\add* swallow up wealth \add but then\add* vomit it up.
\q1 God forces it out of \add their\add* stomachs.
\q1
\v 16 \add They’ll\add* suck on cobra poison.
\q1 The viper’s fangs will kill \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 17 \add Those wicked people\add* won’t enjoy the streams,
\q2 \add or the\add* fast-flowing rivers of honey and yoghurt.
\q1
\v 18 \add They\add* will return what \add they’ve gained\add* and not swallow it \add down\add*.
\q1 \add They\add* won’t get any enjoyment from the profits of \add their\add* trading.
\q1
\v 19 \add They’ve\add* oppressed \add others\add* and ignored the poor.
\q1 \add They’ve\add* seized homes that they didn’t build.
\b
\q1
\v 20 \add Their\add* bellies are never at ease.
\q1 \add They\add* never deliver what \add they\add* desire.
\q1
\v 21 There’s nothing left over from \add their\add* eating,
\q2 so their prosperity won’t endure.
\q1
\v 22 \add They’ll\add* be so full \add but\add* it’ll \add only\add* bring distress.
\q1 Every troublemaker will come to \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 23 Maybe when \add they’ve\add* filled their bellies,
\q2 \add God\add* will send his anger against \add them\add*,
\q1 raining down on \add them and their\add* meal.
\q1
\v 24 \add They\add* flee from weapons made of iron.
\q1 A bow made of brass \add sends its arrows\add* right through \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 25 \add They\add* pull them through and out \add their\add* backs.
\q1 The tips have shiny liver on them—terrors come over \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 26 Total darkness is reserved for \add their\add* treasures.
\q1 A fire \add which no one started\add* will devour \add them\add*.
\q1 Only sorry remnants will survive in \add their\add* tents.
\q1
\v 27 The heavens will reveal \add their\add* evils,
\q1 and the earth will rise up against \add them\add*.
\q1
\v 28 The contents of \add their\add* houses will be removed—
\q2 washed away in his severe anger.
\q1
\v 29 That’s what God serves up to wicked people,
\q1 and the heritage that God has decreed for them.
\c 21
\s1 Iyyov’s second response to Zofar
\p
\v 1 Then Iyyov \add responded to Zofar and the others\add*:
\q1
\v 2 Listen carefully to my words,
\q2 and let this be a consolation for you all.
\q1
\v 3 Bear with me while I speak,
\q2 and after I’ve \add finished\add*, you can continue mocking then.
\q1
\v 4 As for me, is my complaint against any person?
\q1 If it was, then \add you\add* might expect \add me to be impatient\add*.
\q1
\v 5 Turn \add and look\add* at me and be appalled.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* put your hands over your mouths \add in shock\add*.
\q1
\v 6 When I remember \add what happened\add*, I’m horrified,
\q2 and my body starts shuddering.
\q1
\v 7 Why do wicked \add people\add* live?
\q1 \add Why\add* do they grow old and become more powerful?
\q1
\v 8 Their children become established around them,
\q1 and their offspring \add become settled\add* in front of them.
\q1
\v 9 Their homes are safe and \add free from\add* fear.
\q1 God isn’t punishing them.
\q1
\v 10 Their bulls mate \add productively\add*,
\q1 and their cows calve without miscarrying.
\q1
\v 11 They send out their little ones like a flock,
\q1 and their children dance \add all around\add*.
\q1
\v 12 They pick up their tambourines and harps,
\q1 and they’re happy to hear the sound of the flutes.
\q1
\v 13 They spend their days in prosperity,
\q1 and they go peacefully down \add to the grave\add*.
\q1
\v 14 They tell God, “Leave us alone.
\q1 We’re not \add interested\add* in knowing about your ways.
\q1
\v 15 Who is ‘the provider’ \add and why should\add* we serve him.
\q1 What would we gain if we made requests to him?”
\b
\q1
\v 16 \add However,\add* their prosperity isn’t in \em their\em* hands.
\q1 I keep far away from the advice of wicked \add people\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 17 How often is the lamp of wicked \add people\add* extinguished and calamity hits them?
\q1 In his anger, does he dole out pain to them?
\q1
\v 18 Are they \add just\add* like straw \add blown by\add* the wind,
\q1 and like chaff that’s carried away by a gale.
\b
\q1
\v 19 God saves up \add their\add* evil for \add their\add* children.
\q1 Let \add God\add* repay \add them\add* so \add they’ll\add* know.
\q1
\v 20 Let them watch \add their\add* own destruction,
\q1 and let \add them\add* drink the severe anger of the provider.
\q1
\v 21 After they’re gone, why would \add they\add* care about their families?
\q1 Why would they count the months after they’ve already been cut off?
\q1
\v 22 Can any \add person\add* teach knowledge to God
